# Start of question: currents and current densities in two wires of different radii
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:currents and current densities in two wires of different radii
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
Wire A has a radius of 1 mm.  It is connected in series (end to end) with wire B which has radius 2 mm.  The two are now connected to a battery and current flows through them.  Compare the currents, I<sub>A</sub> and I<sub>B</sub> and the current densities J<sub>A</sub> and J<sub>B</sub>
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
I<sub>A</sub> = I<sub>B</sub>, J<sub>A</sub> > J<sub>B</sub>
:ANSWER2:0:H
I<sub>A</sub> > I<sub>B</sub>, J<sub>A</sub> > J<sub>B</sub>
:ANSWER3:0:H
I<sub>A</sub> = I<sub>B</sub>, J<sub>A</sub> = J<sub>B</sub>
:ANSWER4:0:H
I<sub>A</sub> < I<sub>B</sub>, J<sub>A</sub> < J<sub>B</sub>
:ANSWER5:0:H
I<sub>A</sub> < I<sub>B</sub>, J<sub>A</sub> = J<sub>B</sub>
:CAT:Current and Conductivity
# End of question: currents and current densities in two wires of different radii

# Start of question: electron current is the same everywhere (thin to thick) - need to fix figure
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:electron current is the same everywhere (thin to thick) - need to fix figure
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
This question may sound suspiciously like a fluid flow question, and conceptually it is very similar.  A wire is shown which widens from a thin section to a thick section.  A number N<sub>e</sub> electrons pass through a cross section of the thin wire in a second.  The number passing through a cross section of the thick section of wire per second should be
:IMAGE:figures_for_quizzes/current_conductivity/thick_wire_to_thin.gif
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
N<sub>e</sub> (the same as in the thin section of wire)
:ANSWER2:0:H
Less than in the thick section of wire
:ANSWER3:0:H
Greater than in the thick section of wire
:ANSWER4:0:H
Need more information
:CAT:Current and Conductivity
# End of question: electron current is the same everywhere (thin to thick) - need to fix figure

# Start of question: comparing drift velocities (same current, different metals)
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:comparing drift velocities (same current, different metals)
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
A 1 mm thick copper wire has a conduction-electron density of 8.5 X 10<sup>28</sup> m<sup>-3</sup>.  A 1 mm thick aluminum wire has a conduction electron density of 6.0 X 10<sup>28</sup> m<sup>-3</sup>.  Suppose the wires are hooked up end to end and attached to a battery so that the electron current must be the same in both wires.  The drift velocity of electrons in the aluminum wire must be
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
greater than the drift velocity in the copper wire
:ANSWER2:0:H
less than the drift velocity in the copper wire
:ANSWER3:0:H
the same as the drift velocity in the copper wire
:ANSWER4:0:H
need more information
:CAT:Current and Conductivity
# End of question: comparing drift velocities (same current, different metals)

