# Start of question: nature of motion in electrons flowing in a wire
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:nature of motion in electrons flowing in a wire
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
A current in a wire is sustained by an electrical field.  The motion of an individual conduction electron in the wire is best described as
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
frequent collisions with atoms giving random (thermal) velocities, with a constant  acceleration due to the field superimposed on this random thermal motion
:ANSWER2:0:H
constant speed in the direction of the electrical field
:ANSWER3:0:H
constant speed opposite the direction of the electrical field
:ANSWER4:0:H
constant acceleration opposite the direction of the electrical field
:ANSWER5:0:H
random thermal motion with a constant speed in the direction of the field superimposed on top of this.
:CAT:Current and Conductivity
# End of question: nature of motion in electrons flowing in a wire

